"Pours with a small sized head that leaves lacing and a well-defined collar around the liquid. Body is ruby brown, clear and bright. The aroma first off reminds me of banana chips -- dried sugar smells mixed with fruit and a bit of spice. Pears and caramel malts come out with higher temperature and exposure to air. On the palate, big caramel sweetness up front, followed by pears and apples for fruits at the mid-palate. It's very malty, with just some hops for bittering balance. Toward the end there's a tinge of acidity, followed by a quick dry-out leaving a baked dough note for the finish. Mouthfeel is very thick, as usual for the style, with uncharacteristically sharp carbonation that helps lighten things a bit. Overall, this is a good barleywine, made in the English style. It will be interesting to see what aging does to this."
"This beer pours a light golden color with a moderate head. The lacing pattern is also very complete and leaves no piece of glass uncovered. The smell is very, very sweet and almost reminds me of cotton candy. The smell begins to permeate as soon as the top is removed and this beer is poured. The taste is sweet as well. The same bubble-gum smell is apparent, but the addition of strong hops makes this special. The taste is very large, much like a good barlywine should be. This is a beer that should be sought out, and enjoyed thoroughly."
"Fresh bottle dated 10/16/06. Pour was a little carbonated. With a 15% ABV, the alcohol burn was noticeable but not overwhelming. I think this beer needs to age a bit. This beer is very sweet for a barley wine & I can't quite put my finger on its flavors. Still, this is a tasty brew and I will put a few down to sit to see what happens with some age. Cheers."
"Drinkability is pretty good for the huge ABV. This is a long sipper to say the least. Some cellaring time should do wonders for this."
