"The drinkability is great, very enjoyable BIG fruity flavor, very nice. It left me wishing for one more sip. Prosit MK"
"I did a little tasting of the 2005 and 2006 versions of this over the last two days. The new one was bottled on 10/16/2006 and the old one was bottled on 11/10/2005. The appearance was very similar, clear gold with hints of orange. My wife thought I was drinking champagne. The newer one had a bigger and more persistent off white head and was much more effervescent. The new one left lacing down the glass on top of glycerin, the old one just left the glycerin. The smell is a little grassy and some fruit, with a little bit of alcohol. The older bottle had less fruit and more grassiness. The new one reminded me of thick champagne. There is a strong chardonnay flavor in bottles, figs, pears, and a touch of hazelnut. The smells and flavors in the old bottle are mixed together more and harder to pick out, but they are there. I didn't really notice the alcohol level until it hit my stomach, and it really warmed me up. A very sippable beer."
"Medium body with little carbonation. Slight alcohol burn on swallowing, but that is expected with 15% abv. Not as hoppy as some other American barley wines, but still a nice example. The abv does hurt the drinkability somewhat. Another good brew from DFH."
"Found randomly at Sams in fact I think I got the last 4 pack they had. Pours hazy, orangey amber with nice thick head that leaves lacing. Alcohol is present immediately followed by banana, light hop aroma, some bread, and subdued sweet pale malt. As it worms up the sent grows on me, but the idea of imbibing so much alcohol, with so many residual sugars is a little frightening. The taste is much the same as the smell, actually in some senses it reminds me of certain tripels Ive had I think mainly because of the bready notes and the ester quality. For me the real questionable issue is the amount of alcohol, which is defiantly present more so in this than almost any other beer Ive had, in both the taste and the smell. The mouth feel is all right, but there is definite too much alcohol. Honestly I was a little disappointed. I love that DFH is so daring with their brews, but other than novelty sake, this beer is lacking the balance necessary for a super great drink. Coupled with the fact that this is a hard to get beer and expensive I doubt Ill buy this again, but its worth a try for novelty sake"
"Dogfish is slowly becoming one of if not my favorite brewerys the more I sample their offerings and this barley wine is no exception. Pours a murkey orange with a medium head and little to no lacing. Smell is strong with fruit and alcohol presence as well as toasted malts and brown sugar. Taste is much of the same with a heavy alcohol presence and I definately pick up on the fig notes. Mouthfeel is somewhat rough because of it's carbonated burning sensation but overall still a smooth brew given it's AC."
"I christened my new beer only fridge by buying and stocking a 6 pack of the 12 oz bottles. After going to a cocktail party, and not having anything alcoholic to drink, because there wasn't a decent beer there, I treated myself to an Old School. Poured it into a pint glass (I know, I know) and sat down and relaxed. My wife laughed when I said it was the perfect beer for a 33 degree night. It looked beautiful, and very lightly aromatically hopped. Low carbonation, but nice, respectable head. Thought I tasted a hint of raisons, but it turned out, according to DFH, to be figs. This is a dangerous beer, as it goes down deceptively smoothly, with just a hint of an alcoholic after taste - more of a warming effect than a burn. I am glad I have 5 more bottles."
