"2007 edition, bought at City Wide in South Bend a while ago. Pours slightly brown to orange beer with a softer lacing than expected and just a dusting of a white head. Smells strong, and sweetly malty, with a fruity, hoppy punch. A nice big nose, aggressive and inviting. Big flavor too..I've had another aged Olde School once before and this evokes memories of that experience. Big alcohol presence, but the alcohol is wrangled handily by the complexity of flavors. Big fig and prune punch, with a large grassy bitterness. Bitterness is still strong at this 1-year stage, but more reserved than when new. Sweet, sweet malt, like tasting malt syrup from the can. Hints of maple, strawberry, anise, ethanol. Big syrupy mouthfeel, though not as syrupy as some other DH beers. A sipper of a barley wine, but a delicious one. I was forced to drink this before I had planned to due to moving across the country, but it still didn't disappoint, not by a long shot. Very nice."
"Drinkability/Overall: A real style-bender here...BSPA? Imperial Maibock? A testament to the wide variability within the barleywine style. Another one of DFH's ""Look how much booze we can jam into your favorite style!"" beers and once again, they do it well as the 15% does not take over. Little to no hop presence means a mostly sugary and fruity experience. Surely interesting."
"Drinkability: Another virtuoso effort on the strong beer from DFH, though I can't help feeling that they sometimes oversweeten to compensate for high ABV. Nonetheless, turning 15% into a mild pepper finish deserves some credit. In terms of the style, this is a little sweet and not quite as earthy in its fruits as other barleywines. In some ways I give this the same kind of pass I give Sierra Nevada beers - DFH are going to put their own stamp on everything they do, and a little extra sweetness seems to go with this. Check it out, as it's highly drinkable, but this is a beer to take on its own terms rather than as a representative brew."
